05831nam a22007215i 9780801455261DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014552617 a10.7591/97808014552612doi  a(DE-B1597)496642  a(OCoLC)1042029084  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aT15b.A33 2014eb 7aHIS0370002bisacsh04a303.48/31 aAdas, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMachines as the Measure of Men :bScience, Technology, and Ideologies of Western Dominance /cMichael Adas.  aWith a New Preface 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (456 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Comparative History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps and Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface to the 2014 edition -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Before the Industrial Revolution -- t1. First Encounters: Impressions of Material Culture in an Age of Exploration -- t2. The Ascendancy of Science: Shifting Views of Non-Western Peoples in the Era of the Enlightenment -- tPart II. The Age of Industrialization -- t3. Global Hegemony and the Rise of Technology as the Main Measure of Human Achievement -- t4. Attributes of the Dominant: Scientific and Technological Foundations of the Civilizing Mission -- t5. The Limits Of Diffusion: Science and Technology in the Debate over the African and Asian Capacity for Acculturation -- tPart III. The Twentieth Century -- t6. The Great War and the Assault on Scientific and Technological Measures of Human Worth -- tEpilogue: Modernization Theory and the Revival of the Technological Standard -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past five centuries, advances in Western understanding of and control over the material world have strongly influenced European responses to non-Western peoples and cultures. In Machines as the Measure of Men, Michael Adas explores the ways in which European perceptions of their scientific and technological superiority shaped their interactions with people overseas. Adopting a broad, comparative perspective, he analyzes European responses to the cultures of sub-Saharan Africa, India, and China, cultures that they judged to represent lower levels of material mastery and social organization. Beginning with the early decades of overseas expansion in the sixteenth century, Adas traces the impact of scientific and technological advances on European attitudes toward Asians and Africans and on their policies for dealing with colonized societies. He concentrates on British and French thinking in the nineteenth century, when, he maintains, scientific and technological measures of human worth played a critical role in shaping arguments for the notion of racial supremacy and the "civilizing mission" ideology which were used to justify Europe's domination of the globe. Finally, he examines the reasons why many Europeans grew dissatisfied with and even rejected this gauge of human worth after World War I, and explains why it has remained important to Americans. Showing how the scientific and industrial revolutions contributed to the development of European imperialist ideologies, Machines as the Measure of Men highlights the cultural factors that have nurtured disdain for non-Western accomplishments and value systems. It also indicates how these attitudes, in shaping policies that restricted the diffusion of scientific knowledge, have perpetuated themselves, and contributed significantly to chronic underdevelopment throughout the developing world. Adas's far-reaching and provocative book will be compelling reading for all who are concerned about the history of Western imperialism and its legacies. First published to wide acclaim in 1989, Machines as the Measure of Men is now available in a new edition that features a preface by the author that discusses how subsequent developments in gender and race studies, as well as global technology and politics, enter into conversation with his original arguments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aTechnologyxHistory. 0aTechnologyxPhilosophy. 4aGeneral Science. 4aHistory Of Technology. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145526140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801455261423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801455261/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK